Official Gap Acknowledgements

Microsoft
Source — Microsoft Defender for Office 365 Blog, November 21, 2025
https://techcommunity.microsoft.com/blog/microsoftdefenderforoffice365blog/strengthening-calendar-security-through-enhanced-remediation/4456876
Microsoft explicitly states that SOC teams relying on Defender remediation to remove malicious emails face a hidden risk — calendar entries created by Outlook during email delivery can remain active even after the email is deleted, leaving users exposed. Microsoft introduced Hard Delete as a partial fix but explicitly excluded .ics file attachments and events resent after remediation from that fix.

Sublime Security
Source — Sublime Security Blog
https://sublime.security/blog/ics-phishing-stopping-a-surge-of-malicious-calendar-invites/
Sublime Security confirms that even after an email is quarantined at the gateway level the calendar entry remains active. Blocking or quarantining the email does not remove the event that was already written to the victim's calendar during delivery.

Proofpoint
Source — Proofpoint Threat Research Blog, December 2, 2025
https://www.proofpoint.com/us/blog/email-and-cloud-threats/threat-actors-engineer-attacks-to-evade-email-security
Proofpoint acknowledges that direct calendar injection methods — such as Graph API injection or draft-based delivery — bypass the email gateway entirely. When no email is sent the gateway has nothing to scan and produces zero log evidence of the attack.

Microsoft Tech Community — User Confirmation
Source — Comments on the Microsoft Defender blog post above
Community users confirm that even when an invite is flagged and moved to junk the calendar event still auto-appears. The calendar processing happens before the security verdict is applied — meaning the event is already written to the calendar before Defender or Proofpoint has a chance to act on it. Sonnet 4.6Cl
